Communicate Data Findings - Students Performance¶

by Jessika Nunes Caetano¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset was obtainet from Kaggle datasets (url: https://www.kaggle.com/spscientist/students-performance-in-exams) and contains data about students gender, ethnicity, parental education, among others, and also the scores of the students in math, reading and writing. The ideia here is to explore the impact of each of the factors reported in the students performance.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this case, we have three main features to analyse in our dataset: math, reading and writing scores. We can even create a new feature with the mean score for each student.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe parental level of education, luch and test preparation courses will be the main variables of impact in scores, but we will have to test it.

Univariate Exploration¶

First I will analyse the categorical variables of the dataset, using histograms. I will create all the charts in figures below, and them I will make comments about each variable.

  • The first three visualizations contains the plots whose variables can asume only two values. In these cases, I used pie plot.
  • The following two visualizations contain the plots whose variables can asume more than two values. I kept them in a horizontal orientation so that we could see the labels better. I also ordered the categories in a way that made more sense to analyze.

How do math, writing and reading scores vary among students?¶

I created a set related charts: three histrograms, one to each subject. This way we can look at the distributions and also compare the three of them by seeing them side by side.

In [77]:

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)

Math Score: We can see that the math score distribution is skewed, with most students getting scores around 65-70. A few students got grades between 0 and 10. Later on we can try to understand which factors are characteristics of the students who got lower grades.

Writing Score: The writing score distribution has two peaks: most students got grades between 70 and 75 (higher than the math score), but the second peak is located aroud 50-55.

Reading Score: The reading score distribution is similar to the writing distribution, with the higher peak around 70-75. It appears that the students with good writing skills also have good reading skills.

Now, I would like to create a new variable in the dataset: the mean score. I'd like to look at its distribution two. This variable will now become our main variable of interest, since we will calculate it from the math, writing and reading scores.

In [11]:
mean_score = []

#I will iterate through the dataframe creating the array with the mean score
for row in df.iterrows():
    mean_score.append((row[1]['math score'] + row[1]['writing score'] + row[1]['reading score'])/3)

#I will add the mean score array to the dataframe
df['mean score'] = mean_score

df.head()

Bivariate Exploration¶

I won't explore the relation between all variables in the dataset. Instead, I will analyse the relations that seem to have impact in the mean score or in the score of each subject. I already cited a few points that we could explore in the previous exploration. Now I will look deeper into them.

How does Math, Writing, Reading and Mean scores vary by gender?¶

I created a set of violin charts so that we could see the distribution of each score by gender and also compare the subjects (math, writing and reading) and mean score to each other.

In [82]:
plt.figure(figsize = [18, 6])

For this analysis, I will consider that the number of students in each gender does not vary enough to bias the visualizations. I colored each subplot with different colors to separate the variables analyzed. This are some insights we can get from the visualizations above:

  • Female students have a higher median of mean scores.
  • Female students have higher grades in writing and reading scores, but male students have better scores in math. This can also be cause by the hypothesis that students with good reading skills also have good writing skills.

How does the mean score vary by lunch specifications? Are they impacted by them?¶

In [12]:
sb.boxplot(data=df, x='lunch', y='mean score', color=sb.color_palette()[0]);

Mean score vs. lunch: We can clearly see that students that have a free (probably of lower quality than a paid for) or reduced lunch have lower mean scores. That probably happens because those students who eat better also feel physically better and have more physical and mental health in the moments they are studying.

Do students who completed the test preparation course have higher scores?¶

In [13]:
sb.boxplot(data=df, x='test preparation course', y='mean score', color=sb.color_palette()[0]);

Mean score vs. test preparation course: Students that have completed the test preparation course have a better performance than others. The course can be considered then effective.

How does the mean score vary by parental level of education?¶

In [14]:
sb.boxplot(data=df, y='parental level of education', x='mean score', color=sb.color_palette()[0], order = ['some high school', 'high school', 'some college', "associate's degree", "bachelor's degree", "master's degree"]);

Parental level of education: Except for the students with parents that only attended to high school, the higher the parental level of education, the higher the students performance, measured by the mean score. The students with parents eith higher lever of education probably have a better financial condiction, home structure and/or inspiration to pursue higher education. In case of students whose parents did not complete high school, we could suppose that a considerable quantity of them could want to have a different reality for themselves.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Which gender is more impacted by the luch differences between students?¶

In [147]:
means = df.groupby(['lunch', 'gender']).mean()['mean score']
means = means.reset_index(name = 'mean score')
means = means.pivot(index = 'lunch', columns = 'gender', values = 'mean score')
sb.heatmap(means, annot = True, fmt = '.3f', cbar_kws = {'label' : 'mean(mean score)'})
Out[147]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='gender', ylabel='lunch'>

With this chart we can see that females with standart lunch have a 10 points higher score than with free/reduced lunch, while to male students the difference is only 7.3 higher. The color variation from free/reduced to standart lunch is stronger to females than to males.

What is the relation between the math, writing and reading scores?¶

I have an hypothesis that students with good writing skills have also goos reading skills, so I will put these two scores in the x and y axes. I divided the dataframe in two groups: the first 500 students and the last 500 students for better visualization of the data.

In [45]:
plt.figure(figsize = [18, 6])

sizes = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
legend_obj = []
for i in sizes:
    legend_obj.append(plt.scatter([], [], s = i, color = base_color))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sb.regplot(data = df.head(500), x = 'writing score', y = 'reading score', x_jitter = 0.05, scatter_kws = {'s' : df['math score'].head(500), 'alpha': 0.5})
plt.legend(legend_obj, sizes, title="math score")
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sb.regplot(data = df.tail(500), x = 'writing score', y = 'reading score', x_jitter = 0.05, scatter_kws = {'s' : df['math score'].tail(500), 'alpha': 0.5})
plt.legend(legend_obj, sizes, title="math score")
Out[45]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x24d977cbf10>

There are two conclusions that we can get from these plots:

  • Relation between reading and writing scores appear to be linear, positive and strong;
  • Students with the lowest scores in reading and writing appear to have also low grade in math, and the same happens to students with the highest grades. But in the middle of the grade interval this pattern does not seem to be always mantained.

Does the pattern above vary by gender?¶

I will plot two charts similar to the above, the first with female students and the second with male students.

In [48]:
plt.figure(figsize = [18, 6])

sizes = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
legend_obj = []
for i in sizes:
    legend_obj.append(plt.scatter([], [], s = i, color = base_color))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sb.regplot(data = df[df['gender'] == 'female'], x = 'writing score', y = 'reading score', x_jitter = 0.05, scatter_kws = {'s' : df[df['gender'] == 'female']['math score'], 'alpha': 0.5})
plt.legend(legend_obj, sizes, title="math score")
plt.title('Female Students')
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sb.regplot(data = df[df['gender'] == 'male'], x = 'writing score', y = 'reading score', x_jitter = 0.05, scatter_kws = {'s' : df[df['gender'] == 'male']['math score'], 'alpha': 0.5})
plt.legend(legend_obj, sizes, title="math score")
plt.title('Male Students')
Out[48]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Male Students')
  • We can see that female students have have a higher quantity of grades concentraded in higher intervales of writing and reading scores. Their math grade seems to increse with the writing and reading grades, but their math grades seem to be lower than to male students.
  • Male students do not have a performance as goos as females in terms of writing and reading scores, but their math scores appear to be much better than the female math scores. Also, the relation between math score and the other two scores in the case of male students, although is evident, do not appear to be as strong as to female students.
